"""
mkt-context | leviticus | ch 1-4
The five offering types introduced: burnt offering (olah, ch.1), grain offering (minchah, ch.2),
fellowship/peace offering (shelamim, ch.3), sin offering (chatta't, ch.4).
Historical/cultural context: ANE sacrificial parallels, graduated accessibility (bull→bird),
the offerer as slaughterer, fat reserved for deity, salt of covenant, shegagah (unintentional sin),
four social strata requiring different animals, blood inside sanctuary only for priest/community.
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-leviticus-1-4.py
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

LEVITICUS = {
  "1": {
    "1": "<p>Leviticus opens with YHWH calling to Moses from within the completed tabernacle — a continuation from Exod 40:34-38 where the divine glory filled the tent. The book is set entirely at Sinai between Exod 19 and Num 10. Its Hebrew name <em>Vayiqra</em> (And he called) reflects this opening word. The setting inside the sanctuary marks Leviticus as the most intimate of the Pentateuchal books: YHWH speaks from his dwelling place, not from a mountain or burning bush. The Greek title <em>Leuitikon</em> (things relating to Levites) became the English 'Leviticus,' though the book actually deals with all Israel's approach to YHWH, not only priestly regulations.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The five major offerings introduced across chapters 1-7: (1) the burnt offering (<em>olah</em>, chs. 1, 6:8-13), (2) the grain offering (<em>minḥah</em>, chs. 2, 6:14-23), (3) the fellowship offering (<em>shelamim</em>, chs. 3, 7:11-36), (4) the sin offering (<em>ḥatta't</em>, chs. 4-5:13, 6:24-30), (5) the guilt offering (<em>asham</em>, chs. 5:14-6:7, 7:1-10). Chapters 1-3 introduce the voluntary offerings; chapters 4-5 introduce the obligatory reparatory offerings. Sacrificial systems were universal in the ancient Near East — Mesopotamian (Sumerian and Akkadian texts), Ugaritic, and Egyptian systems all involved animal sacrifice, grain offerings, and blood rituals. What distinguishes Israel's system is its monolatrous structure (one altar, one authorized priesthood, one deity), its emphasis on atonement theology, and its explicit grounding in covenant.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The <em>olah</em> (burnt offering) is the most common offering in the OT. Its defining characteristic is total consumption: unlike other offerings where portions belong to the priest or offerer, the entire animal is burned on the altar — hence the LXX rendering <em>holokautoma</em> (whole-burnt). The animal must be from the herd (<em>baqar</em>) — domesticated cattle — and must be a male (<em>zakhar</em>) without defect (<em>tamim</em>, perfect/complete). The presentation at the entrance to the tent of meeting (<em>petaḥ ohel mo'ed</em>) makes the offering a public covenant act, not a private transaction.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The offerer — not the priest — performs the <em>semikah</em> (laying of hands) and the slaughter. This is a crucial contextual point often missed: in Israel's system, the layperson killed the animal; the priest handled the sacred elements (blood, fire, altar). This distribution of roles differs from some ANE systems where priests controlled all aspects of sacrifice. The offerer's personal act of slaughter makes the sacrifice more intimate — he kills his own animal; the death is not bureaucratically managed. The laying of hands transfers identification: the animal represents the offerer before YHWH.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The blood-sprinkling (<em>zaraq</em>) is the priestly act par excellence: Aaron's sons throw the blood against all sides of the altar. The Mesopotamian parallels help clarify what blood-manipulation meant in the ancient world: blood was understood as the carrier of life, and its manipulation at the sacred space was the mechanism of connection between the human and divine realms. In Israel's system, the specific theology is provided by Lev 17:11 — blood makes atonement because life is in it. The north side of the altar is specified for certain offerings (v. 11), reflecting a consistent spatial organization of the sanctuary courts.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The skinning and dismemberment of the animal is performed by the offerer. The skin of burnt offerings belonged to the priest (Lev 7:8) — a practical priestly income even when the offerer received no portion of the flesh. The careful dismemberment (head, fat, internal organs, legs) reflects a systematic process ensuring complete consumption on the altar. Archaeological evidence from ancient Israelite sanctuaries (Arad, Tel Dan) shows altar structures consistent with this burning protocol.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The priests are responsible for the altar fire — they light it and maintain it. The fire on the altar was to burn continuously (Lev 6:12-13 will specify this explicitly). In the ancient world, sacred fires were maintained at major temples as signs of divine presence; Egypt's temples had perpetual lamps; Rome's Vestal virgins maintained the sacred fire. Israel's altar fire functions similarly but is grounded in the Sinai revelation rather than civic religion.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The careful arrangement of pieces (<em>arak</em>) on the altar is a priestly responsibility. The precision reflects the sanctuary's organization: nothing is thrown on haphazardly; the entire process is ordered and intentional. The head and fat are specifically mentioned — the head represents the whole; the fat (<em>ḥelev</em>) is reserved for YHWH (Lev 3:16-17). The systematic arrangement of dismembered animals on the altar was likely visible from outside the sanctuary court and would have communicated the seriousness and structure of Israel's worship.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The washing of internal organs and legs before burning is a purification step — removing dung and digestive contents. This practical measure also signals that even the most basic aspects of sacrifice are performed with care. The phrase <em>reiaḥ niḥoaḥ laYHWH</em> (pleasing aroma to YHWH) is the standard formula for accepted offerings and occurs 43 times in the Pentateuch. It is anthropomorphic language for divine acceptance — not that YHWH literally smells, but that the offering is received with pleasure. Paul applies this language to Christ's offering in Eph 5:2 and to the Philippians' gift in Phil 4:18.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The graduated accessibility of the burnt offering: bull (v. 3) → sheep or goat (v. 10) → bird (v. 14). This descending scale democratizes access to YHWH — the wealthy bring bulls; the middle class bring sheep or goats; the poor bring birds. The same graduated scale appears in the sin offering (ch. 4-5), the cleansing of skin diseases (Lev 14), and post-birth purification (Lev 12:8). Mary and Joseph bring two birds at Jesus's presentation (Luke 2:24), indicating their household's economic status.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The north side of the altar is specified for the flock offering — consistent with the spatial organization of the court. The north side was the designated slaughter area for certain offerings, probably to keep the blood flow away from the sanctuary entrance on the east side. The altar's geography organized Israel's sacrificial activity spatially, turning the court into a purposefully arranged liturgical space.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The same dismemberment procedure for flock animals as for cattle — consistent treatment regardless of the animal's size. The systematic approach emphasizes that the offering's value lies not in its monetary worth but in its proper presentation. A goat properly offered is as accepted as a bull properly offered.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The washing of entrails and legs applies to all burnt offerings. The formula <em>reiaḥ niḥoaḥ laYHWH</em> closes each offering type — the aroma language signals that the offering has achieved its intended purpose of pleasing YHWH. In ANE temple texts, gods were described as smelling sacrifices favorably; the Gilgamesh Epic (tablet XI) describes the gods gathering like flies around Utnapishtim's sacrifice after the flood. Israel uses the same language but locates it within a covenantal rather than polytheistic framework.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The bird offering: turtledove (<em>tor</em>) or young pigeon (<em>ben-yonah</em>). Birds were the minimum viable sacrifice — accessible to the very poor. Their smaller size explains the modified procedure that follows: no dismemberment, different blood disposal. The specification of two species reflects the practical availability of different birds in the Levant — both were common, nest near human habitation, and could be obtained without significant expense.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The priest performs all acts for bird offerings — unlike cattle and flock offerings where the offerer participates. This reflects the bird's smaller scale: there is no skin, and the blood must be drained at the altar side rather than thrown in quantity. The wringing of the neck (rather than throat-cutting) is the standard method for small birds. The blood drain at the side of the altar achieves the same theological purpose as the sprinkling in larger offerings.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The crop and feathers are removed and disposed of in the ash heap on the east side of the altar. The ash heap (<em>deshen</em>) was a designated disposal area for sacrificial refuse — it was clean enough to be near the sanctuary but separated from the altar itself. The east side facing the entrance — the direction from which worshippers approached — was where the ash was deposited, perhaps as a visible sign of ongoing sacrificial activity.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The bird is split at the wings without complete division — it is presented as a whole unit spread open on the altar. The partial splitting exposes the interior for complete burning while maintaining the bird's wholeness. The closing formula <em>reiaḥ niḥoaḥ laYHWH</em> confirms that the bird offering is equally accepted as the bull offering — economic inequality does not create liturgical inequality before YHWH.</p>"
  },
  "2": {
    "1": "<p>The grain offering (<em>minḥah</em>) originally meant any tribute-gift (Gen 32:13-21; 2 Sam 8:2) before becoming a technical term for the grain sacrifice. In non-cultic contexts <em>minḥah</em> describes a gift presented to a superior — which captures something important about the offering: it is tribute, not primarily atonement. The fine flour (<em>solet</em>) mixed with oil and frankincense is the basic form. Fine flour was the most refined and expensive grade of grain — not rough-ground meal. Grain offerings were accessible to those who could not afford animals, though in practice they often accompanied animal offerings.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The priest takes a <em>qomets</em> (handful — the fist-load that could be scooped) as the <em>azkarah</em> (memorial/representative portion) and burns it. The remainder belongs to Aaron and his sons. This division — a token portion to YHWH, the rest to the priests — is the opposite of the burnt offering (entirely to YHWH). The grain offering served a practical function: it provided flour, oil, and frankincense for priestly sustenance. The word <em>azkarah</em> (memorial portion) reflects the idea that the burning portion causes YHWH to 'remember' (zakar) the offerer — a relational concept, not merely a mechanical ritual.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The grain offering is 'most holy' (<em>qodesh qodashim</em>) — the same designation as the holy of holies and as the sin and guilt offerings. This elevated status means it may only be eaten by the priests in the sacred precincts, not taken home. The grain offering thus functions as both tribute to YHWH and priestly provision — the sanctuary economy provided for its servants through the offerings of the community.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The oven-baked form of grain offering: unleavened loaves or wafers. The prohibition on leaven (<em>ḥamets</em>) for grain offerings connects to the Passover/exodus context (unleavened bread as the bread of affliction and haste) and to the principle that fermentation — a process of corruption and transformation — is inappropriate for what is offered to YHWH. The altar receives nothing that has undergone the fermenting process. This is not a hygiene rule but a purity-theology rule about what approaches the divine.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The griddle-prepared grain offering: fine flour unleavened, mixed with oil. The variety of preparation methods (oven, griddle, deep pan) reflects different contexts of preparation — some households had ovens; others used flat griddles on open fire. The grain offering law accommodates different cooking equipment, democratizing the offering across different economic and practical circumstances.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The griddle offering is broken into pieces and oil is poured on it before presentation. The piece-breaking parallels the dismemberment of animal offerings — both are presented in portions to the altar. The consistent oil-mixing creates a unified preparation across all grain offering forms: oil binds the offering and was itself a valuable commodity representing blessing and prosperity.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The deep-pan (or pot) preparation: fine flour with oil. This third method covers all standard cooking vessels of the ancient Israelite kitchen — oven, griddle, and pot. The law's comprehensiveness in covering all three ensures that no available preparation method is excluded from legitimate offering.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The transition from home to sanctuary: the prepared grain offering is brought to the priest, who carries it to the altar. The movement from domestic space (preparation) to sacred space (presentation) is the physical enactment of the offering's logic — it begins in the offerer's household and is completed in YHWH's household.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The <em>azkarah</em> (memorial portion) is burned; the rest belongs to Aaron and sons. The word <em>azkarah</em> appears 7 times in Leviticus — always for the burned representative portion of a grain offering. It functions as a token of the whole: the part offered to YHWH represents the whole offering and the whole person of the offerer. The <em>reiaḥ niḥoaḥ</em> formula signals acceptance.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The priestly remainder of the grain offering must be eaten without leaven (<em>matsot</em>) in the court of the tabernacle — most holy space for a most holy offering. The restriction to the sacred precincts mirrors the restriction on who may eat it (priests only, not their families in most cases). The priestly meal of grain offering remnants is itself a holy act, not merely priestly sustenance.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Two specific prohibitions: leaven and honey. Honey (<em>devash</em>) includes both bee honey and fruit syrup (date honey, grape syrup) — all fermentable sweet substances. Like leaven, honey initiates fermentation and is therefore excluded from the altar. Notably, the prohibition on burning honey or leaven on the altar does not prevent them from being offered as firstfruits (v. 12) — they can be brought to the sanctuary but not burned as altar offerings. This distinction shows that the prohibition is specifically about what is burned for YHWH, not what enters the sanctuary precincts at all.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Firstfruits (<em>bikurim</em>) may be brought to YHWH as an offering but not burned on the altar as a pleasing aroma. The firstfruits were the first portion of each harvest crop — their offering acknowledged YHWH's ownership of the land and its produce. The Feast of Firstfruits (Lev 23:9-14) and the Feast of Weeks/Shavuot (Lev 23:15-21) were organized around firstfruits offerings. Paul applies firstfruits language to Christ's resurrection (1 Cor 15:23) and to believers as the Spirit's firstfruits (Rom 8:23).</p>",
    "13": "<p><strong>Salt of the covenant</strong>: every grain offering must be seasoned with salt; salt must never be omitted. Salt preserves food — it is the anti-fermenting agent, the opposite of leaven. As a preservative, it represents permanence and faithfulness: a salt covenant (<em>brit melaḥ</em>) is an irrevocable, permanent covenant (Num 18:19; 2 Chr 13:5). The command to season every offering with salt connects the individual sacrificial act to the permanent covenant relationship between YHWH and Israel. The altar, as the place of the covenant, receives salt with every offering.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Firstfruits grain offerings take a specific form: roasted grain (<em>qali</em>) or crushed kernels (<em>geres</em>). The roasted grain offering is the most primitive form — direct parching of grain heads over fire, accessible even before the harvest is fully processed. The grain offering timeline runs from the earliest harvested grain (roasted heads) to fully processed fine flour (ground and sieved). The offering system accommodates the entire harvest cycle.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The firstfruits grain offering follows the standard procedure: oil and frankincense are applied. The frankincense (<em>levonah</em>) was imported from southern Arabia (modern Oman/Yemen) and was expensive — its presence in grain offerings elevated their status. The frankincense was entirely burned as part of the <em>azkarah</em>, creating the pleasing aroma that marked acceptance.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The priest burns the <em>azkarah</em> from the crushed grain, oil, and all the frankincense — the entire frankincense portion goes to YHWH, even though the grain is only partially burned. This proportional treatment ensures the most aromatic and valuable element (frankincense) belongs entirely to YHWH. The <em>reiaḥ niḥoaḥ</em> formula closes the grain offering laws.</p>"
  },
  "3": {
    "1": "<p>The fellowship offering (<em>shelamim</em>, also rendered 'peace offering' or 'well-being offering') is the only offering in which the offerer participates in the meal alongside the priest. This communal dimension distinguishes it from the burnt offering (entirely to YHWH) and makes it the closest OT analogue to a covenant meal. The <em>shelamim</em> is derived from <em>shalom</em> (completeness, peace, well-being) — it is an offering of a person who is at peace with YHWH and wishes to celebrate or maintain that relationship. Male or female animals from the herd are acceptable (contrast the burnt offering's male-only requirement).</p>",
    "2": "<p>The offerer performs the slaughter at the sanctuary entrance — same as the burnt offering. The fellowship offering was often a celebratory sacrifice: celebrating answered prayer, completing a vow, or expressing spontaneous gratitude. Its communal nature (offerer eats a portion) made it the occasion for communal feasts. 1 Samuel 1:3-4 shows Elkanah distributing portions of the <em>shelamim</em> to his family at Shiloh — the offering was the occasion for the family gathering and meal.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The portions belonging to YHWH from the fellowship offering: (1) the fat covering the entrails (<em>ḥelev hamekassah et-haqerev</em>), (2) all the fat on the entrails, (3) the two kidneys with their fat. These internal fat deposits are the richest, most energy-dense parts of the animal. In ANE thought, the fat was the vitality of the creature and therefore the most appropriate gift to the deity. The kidneys were associated with the seat of deepest inner life and decision-making (often rendered 'heart' or 'reins' in KJV).</p>",
    "4": "<p>The fatty lobe of the liver (<em>yoteret al-hakkaved</em>) was significant in Mesopotamian divination (<em>haruspicy</em>) — liver examination was a major form of divination in Babylon and Assyria. Clay liver models from Mesopotamia have been found used for teaching divination techniques. Israel's law removes the liver from divinatory use by assigning the fatty lobe to YHWH — it is burned on the altar rather than examined for omens. This may be a deliberate polemical exclusion of divination practices.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The fat portions are burned by the priests on top of the burnt offering wood — the fellowship offering's fat shares the altar's fire with the burnt offering. The layering of offerings on the altar reflects a complex sacrificial calendar: multiple types of offerings could be in progress simultaneously, with the fellowship offering's fat additions placed on the already-burning burnt offering wood.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The flock version of the fellowship offering follows the same rules as the herd version — male or female, without defect. The consistency of the defect-free requirement (<em>tamim</em>) across all offering types reflects the principle that what is offered to YHWH must represent the best of what one has, not the culled or imperfect animals. Mal 1:8 later condemns the practice of offering blind, lame, or sick animals — Leviticus establishes the standard that Malachi upholds.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The lamb as fellowship offering: the same procedure, with the added rule that the fat tail (<em>ha'alyah</em>) of certain sheep breeds is included in YHWH's portion. The fat tail refers to the large fat deposit on the tail of the broad-tailed sheep (<em>Ovis aries</em>), common in the Levant — these tails can weigh several kilograms and represent a significant fat deposit. This is a breed-specific addition to the standard fat portions.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The hand-laying and slaughter before the tent of meeting — consistent with the general offering protocol. The fellowship offering's blood-sprinkling against the altar maintains the blood-manipulation at the sacred space that defines all Levitical sacrifice.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The fat tail removed close to the backbone is added to YHWH's portion in the lamb offering. The careful specification of where the tail is cut (<em>leummat he'atset</em>, close to the backbone) reflects the precision with which even anatomical instructions are given in Leviticus. Nothing about the offering is left to improvisation.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The two kidneys and their fat from the lamb — same as the cattle and flock rules. The standardization of YHWH's portions across all three animal categories (cattle, sheep, goat) ensures consistency regardless of species. The law is comprehensive and species-independent in its logic.</p>",
    "11": "<p><strong>lehem isheh laYHWH</strong>: 'food of a food offering to YHWH.' The fellowship offering's fat portions are described as 'food' (<em>lehem</em>, bread/food) offered by fire (<em>isheh</em>, fire-offering). This language of feeding the deity was common in ANE temple practice — Mesopotamian temples prepared elaborate daily meals for their gods. Israel's law uses the language while implicitly denying its literal application: YHWH does not eat in the way temples literally fed their statues. The <em>lehem isheh</em> formula is metaphorical divine acceptance language.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The goat version of the fellowship offering — the simplest of the three, requiring no breed-specific fat tail rule. The presentation before YHWH is the same: slaughter at the sanctuary entrance, blood-sprinkling, fat burning.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The blood-sprinkling against the altar sides is consistent for goat fellowship offerings. The precision of the ritual — same blood manipulation regardless of animal — ensures that the theological content (blood at the altar = life offered before YHWH) is not diluted by variations in the offering animal.</p>",
    "14": "<p>YHWH's fat portions from the goat offering mirror those of the cattle (no fat tail, unlike the sheep). The standardized description of fat portions (entrail-covering fat, both kidneys, liver lobe) creates a consistent set of YHWH's portions across species, with the sheep exception for the fat tail being clearly marked as a breed-specific addition.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The two kidneys and liver lobe from the goat — identical to the cattle and sheep requirements. The repetition across three animal categories underscores that these specific fat organs are consistently YHWH's portion in the fellowship offering. The repetition in Leviticus (which some readers find tedious) is a legal precision device: specifying the rule for each case separately prevents legal loopholes.</p>",
    "16": "<p><strong>kol-ḥelev laYHWH</strong>: 'All fat belongs to YHWH.' The general rule underlying all the specific fat-portion instructions: the best and richest part of every animal belongs to YHWH. The fellowship offering makes this explicit in summary form. The practical implication for the ancient Israelite: even in a celebration meal that included the offerer, YHWH's portion was the richest internal fat. This is not merely symbolic — it structured the actual food distribution at every fellowship sacrifice.</p>",
    "17": "<p><strong>ḥuqqat olam ledoroteikhem bekol-moshevoteikhem</strong>: 'A lasting ordinance for all your generations wherever you live: you must not eat any fat or any blood.' The double prohibition on fat and blood is the most universalized law in the sacrificial code — extending beyond the land to wherever Israel lives, suggesting applicability even in diaspora contexts. This universal extension indicates these prohibitions encode something about the nature of life and holiness that transcends geography, unlike many land-specific laws.</p>"
  },
  "4": {
    "1": "<p>Chapter 4 introduces the sin offering (<em>ḥatta't</em>) — a distinct offering type for dealing with specific categories of sin. Unlike the burnt offering (general atonement and dedication) and fellowship offering (celebration/peace), the sin offering addresses the concrete situation of having violated a specific command. The detailed structure of ch. 4 — four social classes with different requirements — reflects both a theology of graduated responsibility and a practical graduated-cost system.</p>",
    "2": "<p><strong>beshegagah</strong>: 'unintentionally.' The sin offering applies specifically to <em>shegagah</em> — inadvertent, unintentional, or unknowing violations of divine commands. The deliberate parallel category is <em>yad rama</em> (high-handed sin, Num 15:30-31), for which there was no sacrificial remedy: the person is cut off. This distinction between inadvertent and deliberate sin is fundamental to the entire sin-offering system. Most sins covered in the Torah's sin-offering laws are acts done in ignorance, oversight, or inadvertence — not willful rebellion.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The anointed priest's sin offering: a young bull without defect (<em>par ben-baqar tamim</em>). The priest requires the most expensive offering because his sin has broader communal consequences — <em>le'ashmat ha'am</em> (bringing guilt on the people). The priestly role creates a heightened moral responsibility: the mediator's failure affects the community he mediates for. This is why Hebrews emphasizes that Jesus, unlike Levitical high priests, had no sin requiring his own offering first (Heb 7:27).</p>",
    "4": "<p>The hand-laying and slaughter procedure is the same as for burnt offerings. The sin offering's slaughter before YHWH at the sanctuary entrance gives it full covenant-transaction status: the death of the animal before YHWH is not private but official, witnessed by YHWH.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The anointed priest himself carries the blood inside the tent of meeting — the sin offering for the priest penetrates deeper into the sanctuary than most offerings. This inner-sanctuary blood manipulation is reserved for the two classes of offerer who represent the whole community (priest and congregation). The carrying of blood inside the tent models the Yom Kippur procedure in miniature.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The blood is sprinkled seven times before YHWH in front of the inner veil (<em>parokhet haqqodesh</em>). The sevenfold sprinkling is the completion number — seven applications before the veil that separates the holy place from the most holy. The blood reaches the boundary of the most sacred space, but does not enter it (only on Yom Kippur does blood enter the holy of holies). The spatial penetration of the blood mirrors the seriousness of the offense requiring atonement.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Some blood is applied to the four horns of the incense altar inside the tent — the altar closest to the divine presence. The horns of the altar (<em>qarnot hamizbeaḥ</em>) are the projecting corners that received blood in sin-offering rituals. The horn application and blood-pouring at the base of the burnt-offering altar together cover the sanctuary's altar furniture comprehensively — both inner (incense) and outer (burnt offering) altars receive blood.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The fat removal procedure for the priestly sin offering is identical to the fellowship offering (entrail fat, kidneys, liver lobe). However, unlike the fellowship offering, the priest and offerer receive no portion — the entire sin-offering animal is disposed of differently. The fat portions still belong to YHWH and are burned on the altar.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The two kidneys and liver lobe — standard YHWH portions. The sin offering's fat portions are handled exactly like the fellowship offering's, demonstrating that YHWH's portion is consistent across offering types. The difference lies not in what goes to YHWH but in what happens to the rest of the animal.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The parallel with the fellowship offering's fat removal is explicit: <em>ka'asher yuram mish-shor zevaḥ hashlamim</em> (just as they are removed from the ox of the fellowship offering). This cross-reference within the law is Leviticus's version of legal shorthand: rather than repeating all the anatomical details, it cites the established procedure of ch. 3. Such internal legal cross-referencing indicates a coherent legal corpus, not a random collection of rules.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The hide, flesh, head, legs, entrails, and dung of the priestly sin-offering bull — everything except the fat portions burned on the altar — must be removed entirely from the sanctuary. The complete enumeration of body parts emphasizes totality: nothing of the animal's body remains in the camp. The priestly sin offering has no human beneficiary — not offerer, not priest, no one in the camp eats from it.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The carcass is taken to the ash disposal site outside the camp (<em>el-shar la-deshen miḥuts lammaḥaneh</em>) and burned there entirely. The outside-the-camp disposal is significant: the most sin-laden sacrifices go furthest from the center. The carcass of the sin offering for the priest or congregation carries concentrated moral weight that requires spatial removal from the community. Hebrews 13:11-12 exploits this: Jesus suffered outside the gate to sanctify the people through his own blood, fulfilling the type of the sin-offering burned outside the camp.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The second case: the entire congregation (<em>kol-adat Yisrael</em>) sins unintentionally. Communal sin is possible — a wrong done collectively without individual awareness. The example is a commandment hidden from the assembly (<em>ne'lam min-ha'eda</em>) — they have violated something without knowing it. This addresses the reality of collective moral oversight in community life, not merely individual transgression.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The communal sin offering is the same as the priestly sin offering: a young bull. The equivalence in offering between priest and congregation reflects their parallel representational roles — just as the priest's sin affects the whole community, so the community's collective sin requires the same level of atonement. The elders represent the congregation in the laying-on-of-hands and slaughter.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The <em>ziqne ha'eda</em> (elders of the congregation) lay their hands on the bull's head on behalf of the whole assembly — a representative <em>semikah</em>. The elders' identification act extends the individual hand-laying mechanism to the corporate level: the whole congregation is present through its representative leadership. This creates a theology of corporate representation in atonement.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The anointed priest brings the community sin-offering blood inside the tent — same procedure as for his own sin offering. The priest acts as mediator for communal sin as he does for his own: the same blood-manipulation procedure covers both cases. The repetition of the inner-sanctuary blood ritual for both priestly and communal sin offerings signals that both represent the most serious impurity requiring maximum penetration toward the divine presence.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The sevenfold sprinkling before the veil — exactly as in v. 6. The parallel treatment of priestly and communal sin offerings is deliberate: both require the same level of atonement because both affect the entire covenant community. The priest's sin affects the people; the people's sin involves the priests. The two cases are mirror images.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Blood on the horns of the incense altar and poured out at the base of the burnt-offering altar — same as the priestly offering. The full altar coverage (inner incense altar and outer burnt-offering altar) is maintained for both community cases. The outside disposal of the carcass (vv. 11-12 and 21) completes the parallel — both priestly and communal sin offerings are burned outside the camp.</p>",
    "19": "<p>All fat portions are removed and burned on the altar — same as the priestly case. The consistency of procedure across the two community-level sin offerings (priest and congregation) reflects the legal principle that similar cases receive similar treatment. Leviticus 4 is organized by social rank but unified by procedural consistency within each rank-class.</p>",
    "20": "<p><strong>vekhipper aleihem hakohen venislaḥ lahem</strong>: 'The priest makes atonement for them and they shall be forgiven.' The atonement formula of the sin offering concludes with forgiveness (<em>sliḥah</em>) — the communal sin offering actually achieves its goal. Unlike the Yom Kippur offering (which achieves annual comprehensive cleansing), each individual sin offering deals with specific instances of unintentional transgression. The formula <em>venislaḥ lo/lahem</em> (he/they shall be forgiven) closes each of the four cases in ch. 4.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The second bull is burned outside the camp — the same outside-camp disposal as the priestly sin offering (v. 12). The legal shorthand <em>ka'asher saraf et-hapar harishon</em> (as he burned the first bull) connects both communal offerings to the established procedure. The outside-camp burning is the defining disposal method for all sin offerings whose blood enters the tent of meeting — the most sin-laden animals go farthest from the center.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The third case: the ruler (<em>nasi</em>). The term <em>nasi</em> refers to a tribal or community leader below the priestly and communal level — a chieftain, judge, or prominent figure. His sin offering is a male goat rather than a bull — a significant step down in cost from the priestly/communal bull. The graduated scale of offerings reflects graduated communal impact: a leader's sin affects his followers, but not the whole congregation as the priest's sin does.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The ruler's male goat without defect is brought when the sin becomes known (<em>keasher yoda'at ḥatato</em>) — the same awareness-trigger as in the communal case. The phrase underscores that the sin offering system addresses post-hoc discovered violations, not pre-emptive moral cleansing. It is a remedial, not preventive, system.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The slaughter location for the ruler's offering is the place for burnt offerings — not inside the tent of meeting. The spatial difference between the leader's offering and the priestly/communal offerings is significant: the blood goes to the outer altar only, not inside the sanctuary. This spatial distinction reflects the lower communal impact of a leader's sin compared to a priest's or congregation's sin.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Blood on the horns of the burnt-offering altar only — not the incense altar inside the tent. The blood application goes to the altar in the court, not into the holy place. This is the key spatial distinction between the two levels of sin offering: inner-sanctuary blood manipulation (priest, congregation) versus outer-altar blood manipulation (ruler, common person). The sin offering's spatial penetration reflects the offender's communal weight.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The fat portions are burned and atonement is made for the ruler's unintentional sin. The formula closes: <em>venislaḥ lo</em> (he shall be forgiven). The ruler receives the same forgiveness formula as the priest and congregation — the outcome of atonement is uniform across all social levels. Graduated cost structure, uniform forgiveness result.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The fourth case: the common person (<em>am ha'arets</em>, lit. 'people of the land' = ordinary Israelite without special status). The common person's sin offering is a female goat — one grade lower than the ruler's male goat. The female offering is less valuable than the male, reflecting the further step down in social and communal impact.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The same awareness-trigger: <em>keasher yoda'at ḥatato</em> (when the sin becomes known). The sin-offering system is entirely reactive to discovered violations. The normative assumption is that the person did not know they had sinned; the offering addresses the gap between their ignorance and YHWH's holiness.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The common person lays hands and slaughters at the burnt-offering place — same as the ruler. The common person and leader share the outer-altar blood procedure, distinguishing them from the priest/congregation who require inner-sanctuary blood manipulation. The spatial organization of the court reflects the spatial organization of communal accountability.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Blood on the horns of the burnt-offering altar — same as the ruler. The four-horn application gives comprehensive coverage of the altar's sanctified points. The horns projecting at each corner were where blood was applied in all altar-horn rituals, creating a four-directional coverage of the altar's sanctified space.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Fat removal and altar burning — same as the fellowship offering's fat portions. The <em>reiaḥ niḥoaḥ</em> formula appears here for the sin offering — acceptance language applied to an atoning rather than celebratory offering. The sin offering is received by YHWH as a pleasing act just as the burnt and fellowship offerings are. Forgiveness formula closes: <em>venislaḥ lo</em>.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Alternative for the common person: a lamb instead of a female goat. The two options (goat, v. 28; lamb, v. 32) give the common person flexibility based on what animals they own. The equivalence of goat and lamb for the same offering reflects that species does not matter theologically — what matters is the proper procedure and the defect-free status.</p>",
    "33": "<p>The hand-laying and slaughter at the burnt-offering altar — same as vv. 29-30. The consistent procedure across all variations of the common-person sin offering underlines that the ritual form, not the animal species, carries the atonement meaning.</p>",
    "34": "<p>Blood on the horns of the burnt-offering altar and poured out at its base — same as vv. 30 and 25. The base-pouring of the blood after horn-application is the standard conclusion to the outer-altar blood ritual; the blood not used for horn-application goes to the ground at the altar's base, returning to the earth as the blood-life principle requires.</p>",
    "35": "<p>The lamb's fat portions are identified with the fellowship offering lamb's fat — same internal cross-reference technique as v. 10 (cattle compared to fellowship offering cattle). The formula closes identically to all other sin-offering cases: fat burned, atonement made, <em>venislaḥ lo</em> (he shall be forgiven). The fourfold repetition of the forgiveness formula across all four social classes emphasizes that the sin offering's purpose — forgiveness — is equally available to the priest, community, leader, and ordinary person. YHWH's atonement provision spans all social levels.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-context', 'leviticus')
    merge_comm(c, LEVITICUS)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'leviticus', c)

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
